{"title_page": "Ebba Busch", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name      = Ebba Busch\n|image      = Ebba.Busch.Thor.riksmotet2015.15d686.1710040.jpg\n|caption      = Ebba Busch in September 2015\n|office      = [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Leader of the Christian Democrats]]\n|1blankname      = Party secretary\n|1namedata      = [[Acko Ankarberg Johansson]]<br>[[Peter Kullgren]]\n|term_start      = 25 April 2015\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor = [[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund]]\n|office2      = [[Member of the Riksdag]]\n|term_start2      = 23 September 2018\n|term_end2      = \n|constituency2 = [[V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland|V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland County East]]\n|birth_name      = Ebba Elisabeth Busch-Christensen\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1987|02|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Gamla Uppsala|Gamla Uppsala, Sweden]]\n|death_date      =\n|death_place      =\n|party      = [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]]\n|spouse      = [[Niklas Thor]] {{small|(m. 2013)}}\n|children      = 2\n|alma_mater      = [[Uppsala University]]\n|website      =\n|}}\n[[File:Ebba Busch Thor in 2018.jpg|thumb|262px|Ebba Busch speaking at Sergels Torg in Stockholm the day before the Swedish election in 2018]]\n'''Ebba-Elisabeth Busch'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upplysning.se/person/data/?id=525776fc-61e3-c859-fc62-632aaebb2396 |title=Ebba-Elisabeth Busch |work=Upplysning.se |accessdate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150211221048/http://www.upplysning.se/person/data/?id=525776fc-61e3-c859-fc62-632aaebb2396 |archivedate=11 February 2015 }}</ref> (n\u00e9e ''Ebba-Elisabeth Busch-Christensen''; born 11 February 1987) is a Swedish [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]] politician who has served as Leader of the Christian Democrats since April 2015. She is a candidate in the 2018 Riksdag (Parliament) election, for [[Uppsala County]] and almost all other constituencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/ebba-busch-thor-har-valts-till-ny-kd-ledare/ |title=Ebba Busch Thor har valts till ny KD-ledare |publisher=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |date=25 April 2015 |language=sv}}</ref> Between 2013 and 2020, she was commonly known as '''Ebba Busch Thor''' due to her marriage to [[Niklas Thor]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn to a Swedish mother and Norwegian father, Busch identifies as both [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] and Swedish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebbabusch.com/2009/05/hurra-for-syttende-mai/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091321/http://www.ebbabusch.com/2009/05/hurra-for-syttende-mai/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 March 2016|title=Hurra for syttende mai!!|publisher=ebbabusch.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref> Growing up in [[Gunsta]], near [[Uppsala]], she was a student at the Christian [[Livets Ord]] primary school. She later studied the [[IB Diploma Programme]] at [[Katedralskolan, Uppsala|Katedralskolan]] in [[Uppsala]], and [[peace and conflict studies]] at [[Uppsala University]].<ref>Karl-Anders Lindahl (11 March 2015) [http://nyheter24.se/nyheter/politik/791818-8-snabba-fakta-som-ger-dig-allt-du-behover-veta-om-ebba-busch-thor 8 snabba fakta som ger dig allt du beh\u00f6ver veta om Ebba Busch Thor] {{in lang|sv}} Nyheter24.se</ref>\n\nShe is a member of the [[Church of Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dagen.se/ebba-busch-thor-den-kristna-tron-passar-bra-for-partiledare-1.352819|title=Ebba Busch Thor: Den kristna tron passar bra f\u00f6r partiledare|publisher=Dagen|language=Swedish|author=Jacob Zetterman|date=23 April 2015|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nBusch was the municipal party political secretary for the Christian Democrats councillor Gustaf von Essen in the Uppsala Municipality. In 2009 she assumed responsibility for the budget when Essen went on sick leave, and at the age of 22 she became a substitute municipal councillor.<ref>[http://pdf.direktpress.se/flashpublisher/magazine/5498/page/7 direktpress Ebba Busch ] Retrieved 11 February 2015</ref> Ahead of the election for municipal councillors in Uppsala in 2010, the party suggested that Busch should be placed third on the election ballot, while the incumbent councillor Gustav von Essen would be first.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://segersam.blogspot.se/2010/02/gustaf-von-essen-far-fornyat-fortroende.html|title=Segersams blogg|author=Segersam|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=4 February 2010}}</ref> The party youth organization chairman Charlie Weimers, who did not get to vote in the election, wrote that he thought the party should have Busch at the top of the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://weimers.wordpress.com/2010/02/11/ebba-busch-for-mayor/|title=Ebba Busch for Mayor!|work=Charlie Weimers|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=2010-02-11}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, a closed vote within the party decided the top name on the ballot, and Busch beat Essen by a margin of two votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://segersam.blogspot.se/2010/02/ebba-busch-forstanamn-i-uppsala.html|title=Segersams blogg|author=Segersam|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=13 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unt.se/uppland/uppsala/busch-i-taten-for-kristdemokrater-312641.aspx|title=Busch i t\u00e4ten f\u00f6r kristdemokrater|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=2010-02-13}}</ref> At the election, Busch received 1,679 votes, against only 220 for Essen.<ref>[http://unt.se/uppland/uppsala/busch-i-taten-for-kristdemokrater-312641.aspx Uppsala - Busc i t\u00e4ten f\u00f6r Kristdemokraterna] Retrieved 11 February 2015</ref> Busch served as vice chairman of the Christian Democrat youth organisation until 5 June 2011.\n\nBusch made several comments to the media during 2010 criticizing the then party chairman [[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund]], and what she perceived as his weak leadership following the 2006 General Election. Ahead of the January 2012 leadership election within the party, she supported H\u00e4gglund's opponent [[Mats Odell]].<ref name=\"v\u00e4rldenidag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.varldenidag.se/nyhet/2012/01/28/LIVE-Kristdemokraternas-extra-riksting-har-startat/|title=LIVE: Kristdemokraternas extra riksting har startat|author=V\u00e4rlden idag|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> She was also herself a candidate for the post of deputy party chairman at the same election, but lost to [[Maria Larsson]].<ref name=\"v\u00e4rldenidag\"/> Previous top names in the party have stated that they strongly disagree with Busch making the party into a right wing party instead of a Christian party and have even threatened to leave their party as a result of Busch's nomination, while perhaps the most popular ex-leader of the party, Alf Svensson, has described his disappointment with Busch's worldview.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/Qlamdq/kd-profiler-kritiska-till-hogervridning|title=KD-profiler kritiska till h\u00f6gervridning|work=Aftonbladet|access-date=2018-07-17|language=sv}}</ref>\n\n=== Party Leader ===\nIn 2015, Busch was announced as the suggested successor of G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund as [[party leader]] of the Christian Democratic party, and was formally elected on 25 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=2054&artikel=6115971|title=Ebba Busch Thor to lead the Christian Democrats|author=Sveriges Radio|publisher=Sveriges Radio|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> Her time as leader was long characterized by an uncertainty on how to profile the party, and consistent low numbers in opinion polls. Her early attempts to gain votes by adopting tougher positions on immigration and law and order were thwarted when the Moderate Party usurped that space. This was followed by a return to a focus on more traditional Christian Democratic issues, such as healthcare and family politics. At the same time, Busch continued to position the party in a more conservative direction on other issues like the opposition to Mosque prayer calls, gender science at preschools and calling for harsher penalties for so called honor killings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smp.se/vaxjo/ebba-busch-thor-kd-vi-ar-emot-boneutrop|title=Ebba Busch Thor tar st\u00e4llning mot b\u00f6neutrop|work=Sm\u00e5landsposten|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dagen.se/nyheter/ebba-busch-thor-kritisk-till-genusflum-1.1181737|title=Ebba Busch Thor kritisk till \"genusflum\"|work=Dagen|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svd.se/kd-infor-sarskild-hedersbrottslag|title=KD: Inf\u00f6r s\u00e4rskild hedersbrottslag|work=Svenska Dagbladet|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref> At the same time, she also came under attack from social conservatives inside her own party for participating in the Stockholm Pride Parade.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/ebba-busch-thor-kritiseras-internt/|title=Ebba Busch Thor kritiseras internt|work=Expressen|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nThe Christian Democrats received only 2,9% in a big opinion poll published in May 2018, and the party's fortunes looked bleak. But support quickly grew as the election campaign got under way with the first debate in mid-August. Busch's strong performance in this and other debates was credited in large part for the party's surge in the polls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://omni.se/analyser-busch-thor-vann-var-ettrig-och-skicklig/a/WLK27L|title=Analyser: Busch Thor vann \u2013 var ettrig och skicklig|work=Omni|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/0EAmRo/tittarnas-dom-ebba-busch-thor-vann-debatten|title=Tittarnas dom: Ebba Busch Thor vann debatten|work=Aftonbladet|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref> She ended up leading her party to its best electoral performance in 12 years, finishing well above the 4% threshold.\n\n== Personal life==\nIn 2013, Ebba Busch married footballer [[Niklas Thor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unt.se/sport/nu-har-vi-fatt-tillbaka-en-av-stans-basta-spelare-2630004.aspx|title=Nu har vi f\u00e5tt tillbaka en av stans b\u00e4sta spelare|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=2013-10-08}}</ref> \nShe has a son, Birger, born in May 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/nyheter/kd-ledaren-ebba-busch-thor-har-blivit-mamma|title=KD-ledaren Ebba Busch Thor har blivit mamma|publisher=svt Nyheter|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> and a daughter, Elise, born in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expressen.se/nyheter/ebba-busch-thor-har-blivit-mamma-1/|title=Ebba Busch Thor har blivit mamma|work=Expressen}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2019, Busch announced on her [[Instagram]] account that she and her husband had filed for divorce.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/uppsala/ebba-busch-thor-skiljer-sig-stor-sorg|title=Ebba Busch Thor och Niklas Busch Thor skiljer sig|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019|via=www.svt.se}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150317035614/http://www.ebbabusch.com/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n|-\n{{s-off}} \n|-\n{{s-bef|before=-}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Municipal Commissioner for [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]] in [[Uppsala Municipality]]|years=2010 &ndash;2015}}\n{{s-aft|after=Jonas Segersam}}\n|- \n{{s-ppo}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Leader of the Christian Democrats]]|years=2015 &ndash; present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busch, Ebba}}\n\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Christian Democrats (Sweden) politicians]]\n[[Category:Footballers' wives and girlfriends]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Uppsala]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:Swedish Lutherans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name      = Ebba Busch\n|image      = Ebba.Busch.Thor.riksmotet2015.15d686.1710040.jpg\n|caption      = Ebba Busch in September 2015\n|office      = [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Leader of the Christian Democrats]]\n|1blankname      = Party secretary\n|1namedata      = [[Acko Ankarberg Johansson]]<br>[[Peter Kullgren]]\n|term_start      = 25 April 2015\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor = [[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund]]\n|office2      = [[Member of the Riksdag]]\n|term_start2      = 23 September 2018\n|term_end2      = \n|constituency2 = [[V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland|V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland County East]]\n|birth_name      = Ebba Elisabeth Busch-Christensen\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1987|02|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Gamla Uppsala|Gamla Uppsala, Sweden]]\n|death_date      =\n|death_place      =\n|party      = [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]]\n|spouse      = [[Niklas Thor]] {{small|(m. 2013)}}\n|children      = 2\n|alma_mater      = [[Uppsala University]]\n|website      =\n|}}\n[[File:Ebba Busch Thor in 2018.jpg|thumb|262px|Ebba Busch speaking at Sergels Torg in Stockholm the day before the Swedish election in 2018]]\n'''Ebba-Elisabeth Busch'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upplysning.se/person/data/?id=525776fc-61e3-c859-fc62-632aaebb2396 |title=Ebba-Elisabeth Busch |work=Upplysning.se |accessdate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150211221048/http://www.upplysning.se/person/data/?id=525776fc-61e3-c859-fc62-632aaebb2396 |archivedate=11 February 2015 }}</ref> (n\u00e9e ''Ebba-Elisabeth Busch-Christensen''; born 11 February 1987) is a Swedish [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]] politician who has served as Leader of the Christian Democrats since April 2015. She is a candidate in the 2018 Riksdag (Parliament) election, for [[Uppsala County]] and almost all other constituencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/ebba-busch-thor-har-valts-till-ny-kd-ledare/ |title=Ebba Busch Thor har valts till ny KD-ledare |publisher=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |date=25 April 2015 |language=sv}}</ref> Between 2013 and 2020, she was commonly known as '''Ebba Busch Thor''' due to her marriage to [[Niklas Thor]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn to a Swedish mother and Norwegian father, Busch identifies as both [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] and Swedish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebbabusch.com/2009/05/hurra-for-syttende-mai/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091321/http://www.ebbabusch.com/2009/05/hurra-for-syttende-mai/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 March 2016|title=Hurra for syttende mai!!|publisher=ebbabusch.com|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref> Growing up in [[Gunsta]], near [[Uppsala]], she was a student at the Christian [[Livets Ord]] primary school. She later studied the [[IB Diploma Programme]] at [[Katedralskolan, Uppsala|Katedralskolan]] in [[Uppsala]], and [[peace and conflict studies]] at [[Uppsala University]].<ref>Karl-Anders Lindahl (11 March 2015) [http://nyheter24.se/nyheter/politik/791818-8-snabba-fakta-som-ger-dig-allt-du-behover-veta-om-ebba-busch-thor 8 snabba fakta som ger dig allt du beh\u00f6ver veta om Ebba Busch Thor] {{in lang|sv}} Nyheter24.se</ref>\n\nShe is a member of the [[Church of Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dagen.se/ebba-busch-thor-den-kristna-tron-passar-bra-for-partiledare-1.352819|title=Ebba Busch Thor: Den kristna tron passar bra f\u00f6r partiledare|publisher=Dagen|language=Swedish|author=Jacob Zetterman|date=23 April 2015|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nBusch was the municipal party political secretary for the Christian Democrats councillor Gustaf von Essen in the Uppsala Municipality. In 2009 she assumed responsibility for the budget when Essen went on sick leave, and at the age of 22 she became a substitute municipal councillor.<ref>[http://pdf.direktpress.se/flashpublisher/magazine/5498/page/7 direktpress Ebba Busch ] Retrieved 11 February 2015</ref> Ahead of the election for municipal councillors in Uppsala in 2010, the party suggested that Busch should be placed third on the election ballot, while the incumbent councillor Gustav von Essen would be first.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://segersam.blogspot.se/2010/02/gustaf-von-essen-far-fornyat-fortroende.html|title=Segersams blogg|author=Segersam|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=4 February 2010}}</ref> The party youth organization chairman Charlie Weimers, who did not get to vote in the election, wrote that he thought the party should have Busch at the top of the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://weimers.wordpress.com/2010/02/11/ebba-busch-for-mayor/|title=Ebba Busch for Mayor!|work=Charlie Weimers|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=2010-02-11}}</ref>\n\nIn the end, a closed vote within the party decided the top name on the ballot, and Busch beat Essen by a margin of two votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://segersam.blogspot.se/2010/02/ebba-busch-forstanamn-i-uppsala.html|title=Segersams blogg|author=Segersam|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=13 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unt.se/uppland/uppsala/busch-i-taten-for-kristdemokrater-312641.aspx|title=Busch i t\u00e4ten f\u00f6r kristdemokrater|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=2010-02-13}}</ref> At the election, Busch received 1,679 votes, against only 220 for Essen.<ref>[http://unt.se/uppland/uppsala/busch-i-taten-for-kristdemokrater-312641.aspx Uppsala - Busc i t\u00e4ten f\u00f6r Kristdemokraterna] Retrieved 11 February 2015</ref> Busch served as vice chairman of the Christian Democrat youth organisation until 5 June 2011.\n\nBusch made several comments to the media during 2010 criticizing the then party chairman [[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund]], and what she perceived as his weak leadership following the 2006 General Election. Ahead of the January 2012 leadership election within the party, she supported H\u00e4gglund's opponent [[Mats Odell]].<ref name=\"v\u00e4rldenidag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.varldenidag.se/nyhet/2012/01/28/LIVE-Kristdemokraternas-extra-riksting-har-startat/|title=LIVE: Kristdemokraternas extra riksting har startat|author=V\u00e4rlden idag|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> She was also herself a candidate for the post of deputy party chairman at the same election, but lost to [[Maria Larsson]].<ref name=\"v\u00e4rldenidag\"/> Previous top names in the party have stated that they strongly disagree with Busch making the party into a right wing party instead of a Christian party and have even threatened to leave their party as a result of Busch's nomination, while perhaps the most popular ex-leader of the party, Alf Svensson, has described his disappointment with Busch's worldview.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/Qlamdq/kd-profiler-kritiska-till-hogervridning|title=KD-profiler kritiska till h\u00f6gervridning|work=Aftonbladet|access-date=2018-07-17|language=sv}}</ref>\n\n=== Party Leader ===\nIn 2015, Busch was announced as the suggested successor of G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund as [[party leader]] of the Christian Democratic party, and was formally elected on 25 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=2054&artikel=6115971|title=Ebba Busch Thor to lead the Christian Democrats|author=Sveriges Radio|publisher=Sveriges Radio|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> Her time as leader was long characterized by an uncertainty on how to profile the party, and consistent low numbers in opinion polls. Her early attempts to gain votes by adopting tougher positions on immigration and law and order were thwarted when the Moderate Party usurped that space. This was followed by a return to a focus on more traditional Christian Democratic issues, such as healthcare and family politics. At the same time, Busch continued to position the party in a more conservative direction on other issues like the opposition to Mosque prayer calls, gender science at preschools and calling for harsher penalties for so called honor killings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smp.se/vaxjo/ebba-busch-thor-kd-vi-ar-emot-boneutrop|title=Ebba Busch Thor tar st\u00e4llning mot b\u00f6neutrop|work=Sm\u00e5landsposten|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dagen.se/nyheter/ebba-busch-thor-kritisk-till-genusflum-1.1181737|title=Ebba Busch Thor kritisk till \"genusflum\"|work=Dagen|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.svd.se/kd-infor-sarskild-hedersbrottslag|title=KD: Inf\u00f6r s\u00e4rskild hedersbrottslag|work=Svenska Dagbladet|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref> At the same time, she also came under attack from social conservatives inside her own party for participating in the Stockholm Pride Parade.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/ebba-busch-thor-kritiseras-internt/|title=Ebba Busch Thor kritiseras internt|work=Expressen|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nThe Christian Democrats received only 2,9% in a big opinion poll published in May 2018, and the party's fortunes looked bleak. But support quickly grew as the election campaign got under way with the first debate in mid-August. Busch's strong performance in this and other debates was credited in large part for the party's surge in the polls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://omni.se/analyser-busch-thor-vann-var-ettrig-och-skicklig/a/WLK27L|title=Analyser: Busch Thor vann \u2013 var ettrig och skicklig|work=Omni|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/0EAmRo/tittarnas-dom-ebba-busch-thor-vann-debatten|title=Tittarnas dom: Ebba Busch Thor vann debatten|work=Aftonbladet|access-date=2018-09-28|language=sv}}</ref> She ended up leading her party to its best electoral performance in 12 years, finishing well above the 4% threshold.\n\n== Personal life==\nIn 2013, Ebba Busch married footballer [[Niklas Thor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unt.se/sport/nu-har-vi-fatt-tillbaka-en-av-stans-basta-spelare-2630004.aspx|title=Nu har vi f\u00e5tt tillbaka en av stans b\u00e4sta spelare|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2015|date=2013-10-08}}</ref> \nShe has a son, Birger, born in May 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/nyheter/kd-ledaren-ebba-busch-thor-har-blivit-mamma|title=KD-ledaren Ebba Busch Thor har blivit mamma|publisher=svt Nyheter|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> and a daughter, Elise, born in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expressen.se/nyheter/ebba-busch-thor-har-blivit-mamma-1/|title=Ebba Busch Thor har blivit mamma|work=Expressen}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December 2019, Busch announced on her [[Instagram]] account that and she and her husband had filed for divorce.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/uppsala/ebba-busch-thor-skiljer-sig-stor-sorg|title=Ebba Busch Thor och Niklas Busch Thor skiljer sig|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019|via=www.svt.se}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150317035614/http://www.ebbabusch.com/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n|-\n{{s-off}} \n|-\n{{s-bef|before=-}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Municipal Commissioner for [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]] in [[Uppsala Municipality]]|years=2010 &ndash;2015}}\n{{s-aft|after=Jonas Segersam}}\n|- \n{{s-ppo}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[G\u00f6ran H\u00e4gglund]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Leader of the Christian Democrats]]|years=2015 &ndash; present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busch, Ebba}}\n\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Christian Democrats (Sweden) politicians]]\n[[Category:Footballers' wives and girlfriends]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Uppsala]]\n[[Category:Female critics of feminism]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:Swedish Lutherans]]\n", "name_user": "Kreggon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ebba_Busch"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Chester", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=June 2014}}\n{{one source|date=June 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Tommy Chester\n| fullname = Thomas Holland Chester\n| birth_date = 7 November 1907\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date = 1979 (aged 71 or 72)\n| position = Full back\n| years1 = 1926\u20131936 | clubs1 = [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] | caps1 = 249 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1936\u20131939 | clubs2 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] | caps2 = 51 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 1939\u20131940 | clubs3 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] | caps3 = 0 | goals3 = 0\n}}\n'''Thomas Holland \"Tommy\" Chester''' (7 November 1907 \u2013 1979) was a Scottish professional [[association footballer]] who played as a full back.\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite book|first=Michael|last=Joyce|title=Football League Players' Records 1888-1939|year=2004}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chester, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-defender-1900s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{no footnotes|date=June 2014}}\n{{one source|date=June 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name      = Tommy Chester\n| fullname = Thomas Holland Chester\n| birth_date = 7 November 1907\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date = 1979 (aged 71 or 72)\n| position = Full back\n| years1 = 1926\u20131936 | clubs1 = [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] | caps1 = 249 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1936\u20131939 | clubs2 = [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] | caps2 = 51 | goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 1939\u20131940 | clubs3 = [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] | caps3 = 0 | goals3 = 0\n}}\n'''Thomas Holland \"Tommy\" Chester''' (7 November 1907 \u2013 1979) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] professional [[association footballer]] who played as a full back.\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite book|first=Michael|last=Joyce|title=Football League Players' Records 1888-1939|year=2004}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chester, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Bury F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-defender-1900s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Chester"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Cheetham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tommy Cheetham\n| image = Tommy Cheetham (footballer).jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = \n| fullname = Thomas Miles Cheetham<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n| birth_date = 11 October 1910\n| birth_place = [[Byker]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1993|12|23|1910|10|11|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n| height = \n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Centre forward]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1929\u2013\n| clubs1 = Byker\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = {{0|0000}}\u20131935\n| clubs2 = [[Royal Artillery]]\n| caps2 = \n| goals2 = \n| years3 = 1935\u20131939\n| clubs3 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| caps3 = 115\n| goals3 = 81\n| years4 = 1939\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps4 = 19\n| goals4 = 8\n| years5 = 1941\u20131948\n| clubs5 = [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n| caps5 = 47\n| goals5 = 29\n| death_place = [[Mansfield]], England<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n}}\n'''Thomas Miles Cheetham''' (11 October 1910 \u2013 23 December 1993)<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Cite web|title = Barry Hugman's Footballers \u2013 Tommy Cheetham|url = http://hugmansfootballers.com/player/3420|website = hugmansfootballers.com|accessdate = 10 December 2015}}</ref> was an English professional [[association football|footballer]]. He scored 118 goals from 181 appearances in [[the Football League]] playing as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref name=\"Joyce\">{{cite book |last = Joyce|first = Michael|title = Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939|publisher = Tony Brown|location = Nottingham|year = 2012|page = 57|isbn = 190589161X}}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nCheetham was born in [[Byker]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]].<ref name=\"LCArchive\">{{cite web |url = http://www.redimps.com/archive3/index.mv?cat=players&drop=playerdetsdrop&play=chee01|title = Tommy Cheetham|work = The Lincoln City FC Archive|publisher = Lincoln City F.C|accessdate = 15 April 2010}} Access individual season statistics via Season Stats dropdown menu.</ref> A late entrant to the professional game, he played local football before joining the [[British Army|Army]] and played for his regiment while serving in the [[Royal Artillery]].<ref name=Joyce/><ref name=\"vintagefootballers\">{{Cite web |url=http://vintagefootballers.com/product/cheetham-tommy-image-1-brentford-1939/ |title=Cheetham Tommy Image 1 Brentford 1939 |website=Vintage Footballers |language=en-GB |accessdate=23 December 2018}}</ref> In August 1935, aged nearly 25, he signed for London club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]],<ref name=\"vintagefootballers\" /> then playing in the [[Football League Third Division South]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He made his debut on 4 September 1935 in a 1\u20131 draw away to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]. Although he did not score in that first game, his next two games brought six goals, a six-game spell running up to Christmas produced 11 and from the 35 games he played in his first League season as a professional footballer, Cheetham scored 36 times.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1935.xls |title=Queen's Park Rangers 1935\u201336 |first=Kenneth |last=Westerberg |format=Excel spreadsheet |work=QPRnet |publisher=Ron Norris |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> He set a new club record by scoring in 9 consecutive games at QPR's home ground, [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qpr.co.uk/club/history/potted-history/ |title=A Potted History of QPR (1882\u20132010) |publisher=Queens Park Rangers F.C |accessdate=15 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703220821/http://www.qpr.co.uk/club/history/potted-history/ |archivedate=3 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\nHis performances earned him an invitation to play for the Possibles against the Probables in March 1936 in a trial match for selection for the [[England national football team|England national team]].<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> The quality of the Probables' defence, with [[Alf Young]] outstanding, meant Cheetham had little chance to shine \u2013 ''[[The Times]]''' correspondent reported that \"Cheetham did not receive a pass for nearly half an hour\", but \"considering the brilliance of Young, the play of Cheetham could hardly be considered unsatisfactory\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Association Football. International Trial Match |newspaper=The Times |date=26 March 1936 |page=6}}</ref> Though his next two seasons were less productive,<ref>http://qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1936.xls</ref><ref>http://www.qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1937.xls</ref> in 1938\u201339 he scored 22 league goals from the 26 games before he left the club on 7 February 1939 to join [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] for a fee of \u00a35,000.<ref>http://www.qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1938.xls</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1938.xls |title=Queen's Park Rangers 1938\u201339 |first=Kenneth |last=Westerberg |format=Excel spreadsheet |work=QPRnet |publisher=Ron Norris |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nBrentford brought in Cheetham and [[inside forward]] [[Les Boulter (footballer)|Les Boulter]] to help their fight against relegation,<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{Cite book|title = Timeless Bees: Brentford F.C. Who's Who 1920\u20132006|last = Haynes|first = Graham|publisher = Yore Publications|year = 2006|isbn = 978-0955294914|location =Harefield |page =36|first2 = Frank|last2 = Coumbe}}</ref> though ''The Times'' suggested that their weakness lay less in attack than in defence.<ref>{{cite news |title=The F.A. Cup. To-Day's Fifth Round Ties |newspaper=The Times |date=11 February 1939 |page=5}}</ref> Cheetham made his debut in the top division in a 4\u20132 home defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Association Football. Brentford Lose At Home |newspaper=The Times |date=9 February 1939 |page=6}}</ref> but he went on to score twice as Brentford beat fellow relegation strugglers [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3\u20131 and created both goals in a 2\u20130 defeat of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in early April,<ref>{{cite news |title=Brentford's Good Win. Chelsea Outplayed |newspaper=The Times |date=27 February 1939 |page=5}}</ref> by which time his club had achieved a mid-table position.<ref>{{cite news |title=League Notes. Low-Scoring and Drawn Matches |newspaper=The Times |date=3 April 1939 |page=5}}</ref> He finished the [[1938\u201339 Football League First Division|1938\u201339]] season with eight goals.<ref name=\"Haynes\" />\n\nThe outbreak of the [[Second World War]] in September 1939 put a stop to the Football League for the duration and caused a major interruption to Cheetham's career.<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> During the war, he joined [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref name=\"LCArchive\" /> He played for them in wartime competitions, and also turned out for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = WW2 Guest Players | last = Marsh| first = Steve | website = theyflysohigh.co.uk | accessdate = 8 January 2018 | url = http://theyflysohigh.co.uk/ww2-guest-players/4580849090 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=900&united=Tom_[ww_2]_Cheetham| title=Tom [ww 2] Cheetham| website=westhamstats.info| accessdate = 8 January 2018}}</ref> Then in the [[1946\u201347 Football League]] season, the first full season after the war, Cheetham resumed his prolific goalscoring; 30 goals from 41 games in League and [[FA Cup]] made him Lincoln City's leading scorer. He played only infrequently in [[1947\u201348 Football League|1947\u201348]]. His last game came on 6 April 1948 against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] and he retired from professional football at the age of 37.<ref name=LCArchive/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCheetham was a member of the [[Territorial Army (UK)|Territorial Army]] during the Second World War and was injured at [[Dunkirk evacuation|Dunkirk]].<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> After his retirement as a player he worked for a [[Croydon]]-based building contractors firm in the mid-1950s and lived in [[North London]].{{Citation needed|date = December 2015}} Cheetham died in 1993, aged 83.<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cheetham, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Royal Artillery soldiers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. wartime guest players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tommy Cheetham\n| image = Tommy Cheetham (footballer).jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = \n| fullname = Thomas Miles Cheetham<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n| birth_date = 11 October 1910\n| birth_place = [[Byker]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1993|12|23|1910|10|11|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n| height = \n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Centre forward]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1929\u2013\n| clubs1 = Byker\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = {{0|0000}}\u20131935\n| clubs2 = [[Royal Artillery]]\n| caps2 = \n| goals2 = \n| years3 = 1935\u20131939\n| clubs3 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| caps3 = 115\n| goals3 = 81\n| years4 = 1939\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps4 = 19\n| goals4 = 8\n| years5 = 1941\u20131948\n| clubs5 = [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n| caps5 = 47\n| goals5 = 29\n| death_place = [[Mansfield]], England<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n}}\n'''Thomas Miles Cheetham''' (11 October 1910 \u2013 23 December 1993)<ref name=\"Hugman\">{{Cite web|title = Barry Hugman's Footballers \u2013 Tommy Cheetham|url = http://hugmansfootballers.com/player/3420|website = hugmansfootballers.com|accessdate = 10 December 2015}}</ref> was an English professional [[association football|footballer]].  He scored 118 goals from 181 appearances in [[the Football League]] playing as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref name=\"Joyce\">{{cite book |last = Joyce|first = Michael|title = Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939|publisher = Tony Brown|location = Nottingham|year = 2012|page = 57|isbn = 190589161X}}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nCheetham was born in [[Byker]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]].<ref name=\"LCArchive\">{{cite web |url = http://www.redimps.com/archive3/index.mv?cat=players&drop=playerdetsdrop&play=chee01|title = Tommy Cheetham|work = The Lincoln City FC Archive|publisher = Lincoln City F.C|accessdate = 15 April 2010}} Access individual season statistics via Season Stats dropdown menu.</ref> A late entrant to the professional game, he played local football before joining the [[British Army|Army]] and played for his regiment while serving in the [[Royal Artillery]].<ref name=Joyce/><ref name=\"vintagefootballers\">{{Cite web |url=http://vintagefootballers.com/product/cheetham-tommy-image-1-brentford-1939/ |title=Cheetham Tommy Image 1 Brentford 1939 |website=Vintage Footballers |language=en-GB |accessdate=23 December 2018}}</ref> In August 1935, aged nearly 25, he signed for London club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]],<ref name=\"vintagefootballers\" /> then playing in the [[Football League Third Division South]].<ref name=\":1\" /> He made his debut on 4 September 1935 in a 1\u20131 draw away to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]. Although he did not score in that first game, his next two games brought six goals, a six-game spell running up to Christmas produced 11 and from the 35 games he played in his first League season as a professional footballer, Cheetham scored 36 times.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1935.xls |title=Queen's Park Rangers 1935\u201336 |first=Kenneth |last=Westerberg |format=Excel spreadsheet |work=QPRnet |publisher=Ron Norris |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> He set a new club record by scoring in 9 consecutive games at QPR's home ground, [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qpr.co.uk/club/history/potted-history/ |title=A Potted History of QPR (1882\u20132010) |publisher=Queens Park Rangers F.C |accessdate=15 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703220821/http://www.qpr.co.uk/club/history/potted-history/ |archivedate=3 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\nHis performances earned him an invitation to play for the Possibles against the Probables in March 1936 in a trial match for selection for the [[England national football team|England national team]].<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> The quality of the Probables' defence, with [[Alf Young]] outstanding, meant Cheetham had little chance to shine \u2013 ''[[The Times]]''' correspondent reported that \"Cheetham did not receive a pass for nearly half an hour\", but \"considering the brilliance of Young, the play of Cheetham could hardly be considered unsatisfactory\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Association Football. International Trial Match |newspaper=The Times |date=26 March 1936 |page=6}}</ref> Though his next two seasons were less productive,<ref>http://qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1936.xls</ref><ref>http://www.qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1937.xls</ref> in 1938\u201339 he scored 22 league goals from the 26 games before he left the club on 7 February 1939 to join [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] for a fee of \u00a35,000.<ref>http://www.qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1938.xls</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://qprnet.com/misc/seasonalstats/excels/QPR1938.xls |title=Queen's Park Rangers 1938\u201339 |first=Kenneth |last=Westerberg |format=Excel spreadsheet |work=QPRnet |publisher=Ron Norris |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nBrentford brought in Cheetham and [[inside forward]] [[Les Boulter (footballer)|Les Boulter]] to help their fight against relegation,<ref name=\"Haynes\">{{Cite book|title = Timeless Bees: Brentford F.C. Who's Who 1920\u20132006|last = Haynes|first = Graham|publisher = Yore Publications|year = 2006|isbn = 978-0955294914|location =Harefield |page =36|first2 = Frank|last2 = Coumbe}}</ref> though ''The Times'' suggested that their weakness lay less in attack than in defence.<ref>{{cite news |title=The F.A. Cup. To-Day's Fifth Round Ties |newspaper=The Times |date=11 February 1939 |page=5}}</ref> Cheetham made his debut in the top division in a 4\u20132 home defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Association Football. Brentford Lose At Home |newspaper=The Times |date=9 February 1939 |page=6}}</ref> but he went on to score twice as Brentford beat fellow relegation strugglers [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3\u20131 and created both goals in a 2\u20130 defeat of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in early April,<ref>{{cite news |title=Brentford's Good Win. Chelsea Outplayed |newspaper=The Times |date=27 February 1939 |page=5}}</ref> by which time his club had achieved a mid-table position.<ref>{{cite news |title=League Notes. Low-Scoring and Drawn Matches |newspaper=The Times |date=3 April 1939 |page=5}}</ref> He finished the [[1938\u201339 Football League First Division|1938\u201339]] season with eight goals.<ref name=\"Haynes\" />\n\nThe outbreak of the [[Second World War]] in September 1939 put a stop to the Football League for the duration and caused a major interruption to Cheetham's career.<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> During the war, he joined [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref name=\"LCArchive\" /> He played for them in wartime competitions, and also turned out for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = WW2 Guest Players | last = Marsh| first = Steve | website = theyflysohigh.co.uk | accessdate = 8 January 2018 | url = http://theyflysohigh.co.uk/ww2-guest-players/4580849090 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=900&united=Tom_[ww_2]_Cheetham| title=Tom [ww 2] Cheetham| website=westhamstats.info| accessdate = 8 January 2018}}</ref> Then in the [[1946\u201347 Football League]] season, the first full season after the war, Cheetham resumed his prolific goalscoring; 30 goals from 41 games in League and [[FA Cup]] made him Lincoln City's leading scorer. He played only infrequently in [[1947\u201348 Football League|1947\u201348]]. His last game came on 6 April 1948 against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] and he retired from professional football at the age of 37.<ref name=LCArchive/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCheetham was a member of the [[Territorial Army (UK)|Territorial Army]] during the Second World War and was injured at [[Dunkirk evacuation|Dunkirk]].<ref name=\"Haynes\" /> After his retirement as a player he worked for a [[Croydon]]-based building contractors firm in the mid-1950s and lived in [[North London]].{{Citation needed|date = December 2015}} Cheetham died in 1993, aged 83.<ref name=\"Hugman\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cheetham, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Royal Artillery soldiers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. wartime guest players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Cheetham"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Cheadle", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Tommy Cheadle\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Thomas Cheadle<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1919|04|08|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stoke-on-Trent]], England<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1993|09|04|1919|04|08|df=y}}<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| death_place = [[Bucknall, Staffordshire|Bucknall]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], England<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] / [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1    = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1946\u20131957| clubs1 = [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]| caps1 = 333| goals1 = 14\n| years2 = 1957\u20131959| clubs2 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]| caps2 = 37| goals2 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 370| totalgoals     = 14\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Cheadle''' (8 April 1919 \u2013 4 September 1993) was an English [[Association football|footballer]]. He played for [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] in various positions for over a decade. It was his time as a \"hard-man\" [[Defender (association football)|centre-back]], captaining some of the most successful Vale sides in [[History of Port Vale F.C.|the club's history]], that made Cheadle a legend at the club. He helped the \"Valiants\" to win the [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]] title and to reach the [[FA Cup semi-finals]] in [[1953\u201354 Port Vale F.C. season|1953\u201354]]. He ended his career in 1959, following two years with [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Stoke-on-Trent]], Cheadle worked at Mossfield Colliery and in the local pottery industry before he joined the army.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baggaley |first1=Michael |title=Remembering a Port Vale legend - Tommy Cheadle would have been 100 today |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/port-vale-tommy-cheadle-legend-2733437 |accessdate=8 April 2019 |work=Stoke Sentinel |date=8 April 2019}}</ref> During [[World War II]], in a battlefield in the Netherlands in 1944, he received a [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] injury after throwing a faulty [[grenade]] that nearly went off in his hand.<ref name=\"steele\">{{cite book|last=Sherwin|first=Phil|title=Men of Steele|year=2013|publisher=Pass|location=[[Hanley, Staffordshire]]|isbn=978-0-9926579-1-8|pages=19}}</ref> At a [[Physical therapy|rehabilitation]] centre, Cheadle spoke to Vale trainer [[Ken Fish]], who told him to report to [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] after the war as the club may have a place for him. Playing in Army matches, Cheadle was coached by [[Matt Busby]], who managed to secure a trial for Cheadle for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"PVFC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/FormerPlayers/0,,10381~73414,00.html|title=Tommy Cheadle \u2013 Vale defender from 1946 \u2013 1957 |last=Maitland|first=Chris|date=17 November 2004|work=Port Vale site|accessdate=14 May 2009}}</ref> Cheadle took the advice of Fish and came to [[The Old Recreation Ground]] and signed professional forms in March 1946 for \u00a38 a week.<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|last=Kent|first=Jeff|title=Port Vale Personalities|publisher=Witan Books|page=59|year=1996|isbn=0-9529152-0-0|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Port-Vale-Personalities-Jeff-Kent/dp/0952915200}}</ref> He made his league debut in a 4\u20131 victory against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on 2 March.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> His first goal was against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in a 2\u20131 win on 20 April.<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nSigning as a professional in May 1946, he spent the [[1946\u201347 Port Vale F.C. season|1946\u201347]] season playing across the back four, and also spent time as a [[Forward (association football)|centre-forward]] in a few games.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He played 37 games in 1946\u201347, and scored his first goal in the [[English Football League|Football League]] at The Old Recreation Ground in a 5\u20131 win over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] on 2 November.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> For the [[1947\u201348 Port Vale F.C. season|1947\u201348]] season, Cheadle spent 16 straight games as a striker, scoring a patch of seven goals in seven games.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He hit a total of eight goals in 23 [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]] games in 1947\u201348.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He scored twice in 23 games in [[1948\u201349 Port Vale F.C. season|1948\u201349]], before making 46 appearances as a centre-half in [[1949\u201350 Port Vale F.C. season|1949\u201350]] under the stewardship of [[Gordon Hodgson]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/> Cheadle was one of the starting XI who played in the first match at [[Vale Park]].<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> He played 36 games in [[1950\u201351 Port Vale F.C. season|1950\u201351]], including a draw with [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 28 October at [[The Den (defunct stadium)|The Den]], a game which he played until the end despite breaking three teeth in a hefty collision.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He featured 40 times in [[1951\u201352 Port Vale F.C. season|1951\u201352]], surviving [[Ivor Powell]]'s brief reign to establish himself as a key part of new manager [[Freddie Steele (footballer)|Freddie Steele]]'s first team plans.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He was an ever-present throughout the 49 games in the [[1952\u201353 Port Vale F.C. season|1952\u201353]] campaign, as the \"Valiants\" finished as runners-up in the [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nHe was [[Captain (association football)|captain]] during the [[1953\u201354 Port Vale F.C. season|1953\u201354]] season, where Vale made it to the [[FA Cup semi-finals]] and won the Third Division North title.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> The team had conceded just 21 goals in 46 games with Cheadle at the heart of the '[[Iron Curtain]]' defence consisting of [[Ray King (footballer)|Ray King]] (goalkeeper), Cheadle, [[Reg Potts]], [[Stan Turner]] and [[Roy Sproson]].<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> In the semi-final clash with [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at [[Villa Park]] he was dispossessed for the \"Throstles\" equaliser and gave away the penalty for Albion's winning goal.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> Cheadle featured only 26 times in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] in [[1954\u201355 Port Vale F.C. season|1954\u201355]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He played 19 games in [[1955\u201356 Port Vale F.C. season|1955\u201356]] and 14 games in [[1956\u201357 Port Vale F.C. season|1956\u201357]], as the club suffered relegation under new boss [[Norman Low]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/> His final game was a 6\u20130 defeat to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on 25 March, a game in which Cheadle scored an [[own goal]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nNow 38 years old, he moved to nearby [[Cheshire]] outfit [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] as a player-coach in July 1957.<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> He played 37 league games for the \"Railwaymen\" as the club finished bottom of the Third Division North in [[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]] under [[Maurice Lindley]] and 18th in the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] in [[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359]] under the stewardship of [[Harry Ware]]. He retired as a player at [[Alexandra Stadium|Gresty Road]] in 1959.\n\n==Style of play==\nFormer teammate [[Roy Sproson]] said that: \"Tom was quick and strong and nobody could beat him. Pound for pound, in fact, I would say Tom is the hardest man I have ever met.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sprosonfund.com/Stories/sproson%27seleven.html|title=Sproson's Eleven|last=Harper|first=Chris|date=10 February 1975|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=23 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119231734/http://www.sprosonfund.com/Stories/sproson%27seleven.html|archivedate=19 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In fact he had 22 stitches in the head after various collisions with opposition players, his toughness earning him the nickname \"wooden head\" from his teammates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sprosonfund.com/Stories/goodcompanions.html|title=Tommy Cheadle's good Companions|last=Cheadle|first=Tommy|author2=Dave Porter |date=Christmas 1954|work=Charles Buchan's Football Annual|accessdate=23 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Post-retirement==\nFollowing his retirement, Cheadle became a [[Mail carrier|postman]] in [[Porthill, Staffordshire|Porthill]].<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> The [[pub]] at [[Vale Park]] was named ''Tommy Cheadle's'' in honour of his contribution to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tommy Cheadle's|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/ConferenceAndEvents/0,,10381~2598866,00.html|accessdate=24 July 2012|newspaper=port-vale.co.uk|date=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"12\"|[[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]\n|[[1946\u201347 Port Vale F.C. season|1946\u201347]]\n|[[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]]\n|32||3||5||0||37||3\n|-\n|[[1947\u201348 Port Vale F.C. season|1947\u201348]]\n|Third Division South\n|23||8||0||0||23||8\n|-\n|[[1948\u201349 Port Vale F.C. season|1948\u201349]]\n|Third Division South\n|22||2||1||0||23||2\n|-\n|[[1949\u201350 Port Vale F.C. season|1949\u201350]]\n|Third Division South\n|42||1||4||0||46||1\n|-\n|[[1950\u201351 Port Vale F.C. season|1950\u201351]]\n|Third Division South\n|32||0||4||0||36||0\n|-\n|[[1951\u201352 Port Vale F.C. season|1951\u201352]]\n|Third Division South\n|39||0||1||0||40||0\n|-\n|[[1952\u201353 Port Vale F.C. season|1952\u201353]]\n|[[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]]\n|46||0||2||0||48||0\n|-\n|[[1953\u201354 Port Vale F.C. season|1953\u201354]]\n|Third Division North\n|38||0||8||0||46||0\n|-\n|[[1954\u201355 Port Vale F.C. season|1954\u201355]]\n||[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|26||0||0||0||26||0\n|-\n|[[1955\u201356 Port Vale F.C. season|1955\u201356]]\n|Second Division\n|19||0||0||0||19||0\n|-\n|[[1956\u201357 Port Vale F.C. season|1956\u201357]]\n|Second Division\n|14||0||0||0||14||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!333!!14!!25!!0!!358!!14\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n|[[1957\u201358 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|1957\u201358]]\n|Third Division North\n|32||0||1||0||33||0\n|-\n|[[1958\u201359 Crewe Alexandra F.C. season|1958\u201359]]\n|[[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]]\n|5||0||1||0||6||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!37!!0!!2!!0!!39!!0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!370!!14!!27!!0!!397!!14\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n;Port Vale\n*[[Football League Third Division North]] runner-up: [[1952\u201353 Port Vale F.C. season|1952\u201353]]\n*[[Football League Third Division North]] winner: [[1953\u201354 Port Vale F.C. season|1953\u201354]]<ref>{{Citation|last1=Sherwin|first1=Phil|last2=Askey|first2=Steve|title=Men of Steele: The story of Port Vale's stunning 1953/54 season|publisher=Pass Publishing|year=2013|isbn=978-0-9926579-1-8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cheadle, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bucknall, Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stoke-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Tommy Cheadle\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Thomas Cheadle<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1919|04|08|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stoke-on-Trent]], England<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1993|09|04|1919|04|08|df=y}}<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| death_place = [[Bucknall, Staffordshire|Bucknall]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], England<ref name=\"Kent\" />\n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] / [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1    = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1946\u20131957| clubs1 = [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]| caps1 = 333| goals1 = 14\n| years2 = 1957\u20131959| clubs2 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]| caps2 = 37| goals2 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 370| totalgoals     = 14\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Cheadle''' (8 April 1919 \u2013 4 September 1993) was an English [[Association football|footballer]]. He played for [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] in various positions for over a decade. It was his time as a \"hard-man\" [[Defender (association football)|centre-back]], captaining some of the most successful Vale sides in [[History of Port Vale F.C.|the club's history]], that made Cheadle a legend at the club. He helped the \"Valiants\" to win the [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]] title and to reach the [[FA Cup semi-finals]] in [[1953\u201354 Port Vale F.C. season|1953\u201354]]. He ended his career in 1959, following two years with [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Stoke-on-Trent]], Cheadle worked at Mossfield Colliery and in the local pottery industry before he joined the army.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baggaley |first1=Michael |title=Remembering a Port Vale legend - Tommy Cheadle would have been 100 today |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/port-vale-tommy-cheadle-legend-2733437 |accessdate=8 April 2019 |work=Stoke Sentinel |date=8 April 2019}}</ref> During [[World War II]], in a battlefield in the [[Netherlands]] in 1944, he received a [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] injury after throwing a faulty [[grenade]] that nearly went off in his hand.<ref name=\"steele\">{{cite book|last=Sherwin|first=Phil|title=Men of Steele|year=2013|publisher=Pass|location=[[Hanley, Staffordshire]]|isbn=978-0-9926579-1-8|pages=19}}</ref> At a [[Physical therapy|rehabilitation]] centre, Cheadle spoke to Vale trainer [[Ken Fish]], who told him to report to [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] after the war as the club may have a place for him. Playing in Army matches, Cheadle was coached by [[Matt Busby]], who managed to secure a trial for Cheadle for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref name=\"PVFC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/FormerPlayers/0,,10381~73414,00.html|title=Tommy Cheadle \u2013 Vale defender from 1946 \u2013 1957 |last=Maitland|first=Chris|date=17 November 2004|work=Port Vale site|accessdate=14 May 2009}}</ref> Cheadle took the advice of Fish and came to [[The Old Recreation Ground]] and signed professional forms in March 1946 for \u00a38 a week.<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|last=Kent|first=Jeff|title=Port Vale Personalities|publisher=Witan Books|page=59|year=1996|isbn=0-9529152-0-0|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Port-Vale-Personalities-Jeff-Kent/dp/0952915200}}</ref> He made his league debut in a 4\u20131 victory against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] on 2 March.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> His first goal was against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in a 2\u20131 win on 20 April.<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nSigning as a professional in May 1946, he spent the [[1946\u201347 Port Vale F.C. season|1946\u201347]] season playing across the back four, and also spent time as a [[Forward (association football)|centre-forward]] in a few games.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He played 37 games in 1946\u201347, and scored his first goal in the [[English Football League|Football League]] at The Old Recreation Ground in a 5\u20131 win over [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] on 2 November.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> For the [[1947\u201348 Port Vale F.C. season|1947\u201348]] season, Cheadle spent 16 straight games as a striker, scoring a patch of seven goals in seven games.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He hit a total of eight goals in 23 [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]] games in 1947\u201348.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He scored twice in 23 games in [[1948\u201349 Port Vale F.C. season|1948\u201349]], before making 46 appearances as a centre-half in [[1949\u201350 Port Vale F.C. season|1949\u201350]] under the stewardship of [[Gordon Hodgson]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/> Cheadle was one of the starting XI who played in the first match at [[Vale Park]].<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> He played 36 games in [[1950\u201351 Port Vale F.C. season|1950\u201351]], including a draw with [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 28 October at [[The Den (defunct stadium)|The Den]], a game which he played until the end despite breaking three teeth in a hefty collision.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He featured 40 times in [[1951\u201352 Port Vale F.C. season|1951\u201352]], surviving [[Ivor Powell]]'s brief reign to establish himself as a key part of new manager [[Freddie Steele (footballer)|Freddie Steele]]'s first team plans.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He was an ever-present throughout the 49 games in the [[1952\u201353 Port Vale F.C. season|1952\u201353]] campaign, as the \"Valiants\" finished as runners-up in the [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nHe was [[Captain (association football)|captain]] during the [[1953\u201354 Port Vale F.C. season|1953\u201354]] season, where Vale made it to the [[FA Cup semi-finals]] and won the Third Division North title.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> The team had conceded just 21 goals in 46 games with Cheadle at the heart of the '[[Iron Curtain]]' defence consisting of [[Ray King (footballer)|Ray King]] (goalkeeper), Cheadle, [[Reg Potts]], [[Stan Turner]] and [[Roy Sproson]].<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> In the semi-final clash with [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] at [[Villa Park]] he was dispossessed for the \"Throstles\" equaliser and gave away the penalty for Albion's winning goal.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> Cheadle featured only 26 times in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] in [[1954\u201355 Port Vale F.C. season|1954\u201355]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/> He played 19 games in [[1955\u201356 Port Vale F.C. season|1955\u201356]] and 14 games in [[1956\u201357 Port Vale F.C. season|1956\u201357]], as the club suffered relegation under new boss [[Norman Low]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/> His final game was a 6\u20130 defeat to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on 25 March, a game in which Cheadle scored an [[own goal]].<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nNow 38 years old, he moved to nearby [[Cheshire]] outfit [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] as a player-coach in July 1957.<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> He played 37 league games for the \"Railwaymen\" as the club finished bottom of the Third Division North in [[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]] under [[Maurice Lindley]] and 18th in the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] in [[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359]] under the stewardship of [[Harry Ware]]. He retired as a player at [[Alexandra Stadium|Gresty Road]] in 1959.\n\n==Style of play==\nFormer teammate [[Roy Sproson]] said that: \"Tom was quick and strong and nobody could beat him. Pound for pound, in fact, I would say Tom is the hardest man I have ever met.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sprosonfund.com/Stories/sproson%27seleven.html|title=Sproson's Eleven|last=Harper|first=Chris|date=10 February 1975|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=23 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119231734/http://www.sprosonfund.com/Stories/sproson%27seleven.html|archivedate=19 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In fact he had 22 stitches in the head after various collisions with opposition players, his toughness earning him the nickname \"wooden head\" from his teammates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sprosonfund.com/Stories/goodcompanions.html|title=Tommy Cheadle's good Companions|last=Cheadle|first=Tommy|author2=Dave Porter |date=Christmas 1954|work=Charles Buchan's Football Annual|accessdate=23 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Post-retirement==\nFollowing his retirement, Cheadle became a [[Mail carrier|postman]] in [[Porthill, Staffordshire|Porthill]].<ref name=\"PVFC\" /> The [[pub]] at [[Vale Park]] was named ''Tommy Cheadle's'' in honour of his contribution to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tommy Cheadle's|url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/ConferenceAndEvents/0,,10381~2598866,00.html|accessdate=24 July 2012|newspaper=port-vale.co.uk|date=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"12\"|[[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]\n|[[1946\u201347 Port Vale F.C. season|1946\u201347]]\n|[[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]]\n|32||3||5||0||37||3\n|-\n|[[1947\u201348 Port Vale F.C. season|1947\u201348]]\n|Third Division South\n|23||8||0||0||23||8\n|-\n|[[1948\u201349 Port Vale F.C. season|1948\u201349]]\n|Third Division South\n|22||2||1||0||23||2\n|-\n|[[1949\u201350 Port Vale F.C. season|1949\u201350]]\n|Third Division South\n|42||1||4||0||46||1\n|-\n|[[1950\u201351 Port Vale F.C. season|1950\u201351]]\n|Third Division South\n|32||0||4||0||36||0\n|-\n|[[1951\u201352 Port Vale F.C. season|1951\u201352]]\n|Third Division South\n|39||0||1||0||40||0\n|-\n|[[1952\u201353 Port Vale F.C. season|1952\u201353]]\n|[[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]]\n|46||0||2||0||48||0\n|-\n|[[1953\u